         <TR BGCOLOR="#000000"><Td ALIGN="LEFT">
         <FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana" COLOR="#c0c0c0">
         <blockquote>
         &gt;The class/level system when multi classing <BR>&gt;is allowed and there is <BR>&gt;an easily attainable max level <BR>&gt; (NWN/DSO) quickly becomes a <BR>&gt;system where there is no <BR>&gt;different classes and no different <BR>&gt;levels.   Essentially making <BR>&gt;it a system where there <BR>&gt;is no class or level. <P>Shadowbane's 'class' system refers to different kinds of player characters, that have different character backgrounds, different strengths and skills, and can /do different things/. Such a system is meant to keep single characters from being able to do just about everything meaningful (think UO tank mages), requiring players of a diverse class base to work together.<P>EQ's class system is inherently busted; not every class has a defined role. Granted, not everyone in Shadowbane is going to want to play every available class (imagine an uberguild of nothing but Confessors,) but IF Wolfpack can give each class a role in the grand scheme of things, then the system will be good enough.<P>As for levels, yeah, leveling can't be the main focus of the game, when everyone's fighting each other, winning and dying. If you assume that in every fight, half the players will lose, then the losing half will need a reasonable means to pick themselves up and get back in to fight again. Otherwise, all but the most rabidly hard-core PvPers and no-life 24/7 levelers are going to get forced out, and Shadowbane will be an empty game.<P>J.<BR>damned vulpine<BR><a href="http://sb.xrgaming.net/" target="_blank">http://sb.xrgaming.net/</a>
         </blockquote>
